The United Nations set aside $1 million to assess environmental damage caused by this week's devastating tsunami, as reports of destroyed coral reefs and uprooted mangrove forests began trickling in.
Coral reefs, mangroves, fish and other marine life had been damaged by the tsunamis which rose out of the Indian Ocean  triggered by a massive earthquake near the Indonesian island of Sumatra.
They are vital for coastal protection from the sea, the U.N.
The agency reported one case in Thailand where the mangroves also damaged shallow coral reefs.
Mangroves grow in thickets along tropical coastlines and their complicated root systems
